5.1 A data management challenge

A data management challenge

  • Lets consider a data management problem.

  • A group of students have taken exams in Math, Science, and English.

  • You want to combine these scores in order to determine a single performance indicator for each student.

  • Additionally, you want to assign an A to the top 20% of student, a B to the next 20%, and so on.

  • Finally, you want to sort the students alphabetically.

A data management challenge

5.2 Numerical and character functions

Numerical and character functions

  • Looking at the this dataset, several obstacles are immediately evident.

    • First, scores on the three exams arent comparable.
    • Second, youll need a method of determining a students percentile rank on this score in order to assign a grade.
    • Third, theres a single field for names, complicating the task of sorting students.

  • Each of these tasks can be accomplished through the judicious use of Rs numerical and character functions.

Probability functions

  • In R, probability functions take the form: [dpqr]distribution_abbreviation()

  • Where the first letter refers to the aspect of the distribution returned:

    • d = density
    • p = distribution function
    • q = quantile function
    • r = random generation

Character functions

A solution for our data management challenge

  • Your challenge is to combine subject test scores into a single performance indicator for each student, grade each student from A to F based on their relative standing, and sort the roster by students last name, followed by first name.

  • The code will be dense, so lets walk through the solution step by step:

5.4 Control flow

Control flow

  • For the syntax examples throughout this section, keep the following in mind:

  • statement is a single R statement or a compound statement.

    • cond is an expression that resolves to true or false.
    • expr is a statement that evaluates to a number or character string
    • seq is a sequence of numbers or character strings

Repetition and looping

  • Looping constructs repetitively execute a statement or series of statements until a condition isnt true.

  • The for loop executes a statement repetitively until a variables value is no longer contained in the sequence seq.

    • for (var in seq) statement

  • A while loop executes a statement repetitively until the condition is no longer true.

    • while (cond) statement

conditional execution

  • In conditional execution, a statement or statements are only executed if a specified condition is met.

  • The if-else control structure executes a statement if a given condition is true

    • if (cond) statement
    • if (cond) statement1 else statement2

  • The ifelse construct is a compact and vectorized version of the if-else construct.

    • ifelse(cond, statement1, statement2)

  • switch chooses statements based on the value of an expression.

    • switch(expr,...)

conditional execution

feelings = c("sad", "afraid")
for (i in feelings) {
    print(switch(i, happy = "I am glad you are happy", afraid = "There is nothing to fear", 
        sad = "Cheer up", angry = "Calm down now"))
}
## [1] "Cheer up"
## [1] "There is nothing to fear"

5.5 User-written functions

User-written functions

  • One of Rs greatest strengths is the users ability to add functions.

  • The structure of a function looks like this:

    • myfunction <- function(arg1, arg2, ...){

      • statement
      • return(object)

    • }

User-written functions

mystats <- function(x, parametric = TRUE, print = FALSE) {
    if (parametric) {
        center <- mean(x)
        spread <- sd(x)
    } else {
        center <- median(x)
        spread <- mad(x)  #median absolute deviation
    }
    if (print & parametric) {
        cat("Mean=", center, "\n", "SD=", spread, "\n")
    } else if (print & !parametric) {
        cat("Median=", center, "\n", "MAD=", spread, "\n")
    }
    result <- list(center = center, spread = spread)
    return(result)
}
set.seed(1234)
x <- rnorm(500)
y <- mystats(x)
y <- mystats(x, parametric = FALSE, print = TRUE)
## Median= -0.021 
##  MAD= 1

5.6 Aggregation and restructuring

Aggregation and restructuring

  • R provides a number of powerful methods for aggregating and reshaping data.

  • When you aggregate dat, you replace groups of observations with summary statistics based on those observations.

  • When you reshape data, you alter the structure determining how the data is organized.

Transpose

  • Use the t() function to transpose a matrix or a data frame.

    cars <- mtcars[1:5, 1:4]
cars
    ##                   mpg cyl disp  hp
## Mazda RX4          21   6  160 110
## Mazda RX4 Wag      21   6  160 110
## Datsun 710         23   4  108  93
## Hornet 4 Drive     21   6  258 110
## Hornet Sportabout  19   8  360 175
    t(cars)
    ##      Mazda RX4 Mazda RX4 Wag Datsun 710 Hornet 4 Drive Hornet Sportabout
## mpg         21            21         23             21                19
## cyl          6             6          4              6                 8
## disp       160           160        108            258               360
## hp         110           110         93            110               175

Aggregating data

  • Its relatively easy to collapse data in R using one or more by variables and a defined function.

  • The format is aggregate(x, by, FUN), where

    • x is the data object to be collapsed,
    • by is a list of variable that will be crossed to form the new observation,
    • and FUN is the scalar function used to calculate summary statistics that will make up the new observation values.

Aggregating data

options(digits = 3)
aggdata <- aggregate(mtcars, by = list(mtcars$cyl, mtcars$gear), FUN = mean, 
    na.rm = TRUE)

The reshape2 package

  • The reshape2 package is a tremendously versatile approach to both restructuring and aggregating datasets.

  • It lets you flexibly restructure and aggregate data using just two functions: melt and cast.

  • Basically, youll melt data so that each row is a unique ID-variable combination.

  • Then youll cast the melted data into any shape you desire.

The reshape2 package

  • The dataset well be working with is:

    ID = c(1, 1, 2, 2)
Time = c(1, 2, 1, 2)
X1 = c(5, 3, 6, 2)
X2 = c(6, 5, 1, 4)
mydata = data.frame(ID, Time, X1, X2)
mydata
    ##   ID Time X1 X2
## 1  1    1  5  6
## 2  1    2  3  5
## 3  2    1  6  1
## 4  2    2  2  4

The reshape2 package

  • When you melt a dataset, you restructure it into a format where each measured variable is in its own row, along with the ID variables needed to uniquely identify it.

    library(reshape2)
md = melt(mydata, id = c("ID", "Time"))
md
    ##   ID Time variable value
## 1  1    1       X1     5
## 2  1    2       X1     3
## 3  2    1       X1     6
## 4  2    2       X1     2
## 5  1    1       X2     6
## 6  1    2       X2     5
## 7  2    1       X2     1
## 8  2    2       X2     4

The reshape2 package

  • The cast() function starts with melted data and reshapes it using a formula that you provide and an (optional) function used to aggregate the data.

  • The format is

    • newdata <- cast(md, formula, FUN)

  • where md is the melted data, formula describes the desired end result, and FUN is the (optional) aggregating function.

  • The formula takes the form:

    • rowvar1 + rowvar2 + ... ~ colvar1 + colvar2 + ...

The reshape2 package
